08564nam a22010695i 9780812207309DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979628228  a97808122073097 a10.9783/97808122073092doi  a(DE-B1597)449631  a(OCoLC)823718180  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0260002bisacsh04a307.3416097304aThe City After Abandonment /ced. by June Manning Thomas, Margaret Dewar. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b25 illus  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe City in the Twenty-First Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The City After Abandonment -- tPart I. What Does the City Become After Abandonment? -- tChapter 1. Community Gardens and Urban Agriculture as Antithesis to Abandonment: Exploring a Citizenship- Land Model -- tChapter 2. Building Affordable Housing in Cities After Abandonment: The Case of Low Income Housing Tax Credit Developments in Detroit -- tChapter 3. Detroit Art City: Urban Decline, Aesthetic Production, Public Interest -- tPart II. What Makes a Difference in What Cities Become After Abandonment? -- tChapter 4. Decline- Oriented Urban Governance in Youngstown, Ohio -- tChapter 5. Targeting Neighborhoods, Stimulating Markets: The Role of Political, Institutional, and Technical Factors in Three Cities -- tChapter 6. Recovery in a Shrinking City: Challenges to Rightsizing Post- Katrina New Orleans -- tChapter 7. Missing New Orleans: Lessons from the CDC Sector on Vacancy, Abandonment, and Reconstructing the Crescent City -- tChapter 8. What Helps or Hinders Nonprofit Developers in Reusing Vacant, Abandoned, and Contaminated Property? -- tChapter 9. Targeting Strategies of Three Detroit CDCs -- tPart III. What Should the City Become After Abandonment? -- tChapter 10. Strategic Thinking for Distressed Neighborhoods -- tChapter 11. The Promise of Sustainability Planning for Regenerating Older Industrial Cities -- tChapter 12. Rightsizing Shrinking Cities: The Urban Design Dimension -- tChapter 13. Planning for Better, Smaller Places After Population Loss: Lessons from Youngstown and Flint -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA number of U.S. cities, former manufacturing centers of the Northeast and Midwest, have suffered such dramatic losses in population and employment that urban experts have put them in a class by themselves, calling them "rustbelt cities," "shrinking cities," and more recently "legacy cities." This decline has led to property disinvestment, extensive demolition, and abandonment. While much policy and planning have focused on growth and redevelopment, little research has investigated the conditions of disinvested places and why some improvement efforts have greater impact than others.The City After Abandonment brings together essays from top urban planning experts to focus on policy and planning issues related to three questions. What are cities becoming after abandonment? The rise of community gardens and artists' installations in Detroit and St. Louis reveal numerous unexamined impacts of population decline on the development of these cities. Why these outcomes? By analyzing post-hurricane policy in New Orleans, the acceptance of becoming a smaller city in Youngstown, Ohio, and targeted assistance to small areas of Baltimore, Cleveland, and Detroit, this book assesses how varied institutions and policies affect the process of change in cities where demand for property is very weak. What should abandoned areas of cities become? Assuming growth is not a choice, this book assesses widely cited formulas for addressing vacancy; analyzes the sustainability plans of Cleveland, Buffalo, Philadelphia, and Baltimore; suggests an urban design scheme for shrinking cities; and lays out ways policymakers and planners can approach the future through processes and ideas that differ from those in growing cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCity planningzUnited States. 0aPOLITICAL SCIENCEvPublic PolicyvRegional Planning. 0aUrban policyzUnited States. 0aUrban renewalzUnited States. 4aPolitical Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Regional Planning.2bisacsh  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.  aUrban Studies.1 aBates, Lisa K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeauregard, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeng, Lan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewar, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewar, Margaret, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEhrenfeucht, Renia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerscher, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawson, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLowe, Jeffrey S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Abbilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorrison, Hunter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelson, Marla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRyan, Brent D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchatz, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchilling, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular